Yeh pretty sure that you can use timestamp as it maps to a slot. The timestamp is always the start of the slot. You can confirm this by grabbing the Genesis block from the daemon:
```gql
query {
  genesisBlock {
    protocolState {
      consensusState {
        slotSinceGenesis
      }
      blockchainState {
        utcDate
      }
    }
  }
}
```
So that gives us 1677182401000 and then grab a latest block and the timestamp of the block is just `1677182401000 + (slotSinceGenesis * 180000)` as 3 min slots. At the time of posting block 13819 has a utcDate of 1679669821000 and produced for slot 13819. So you can use either slot or timestamp to the same effect.

